More Obituaries for David Farahi


Looking for an obituary for a different person with this name?












David (Davoud) Farahi


Obituary
Condolences


































 David (Davoud) FarahiFeb. 13, 1916June 24, 2012David (Davoud) Farahi was born in Tehran, Iran on February 13, 1916, into an observant Jewish family. He was the third of six children. His father worked as a tailor and his mother was a homemaker. David studied pharmacy and graduated from the University of Tehran. He became an entrepreneur who succeeded in many varied business ventures, starting as distributor of medical supplies. With his business partners, he developed one of the largest chicken hatcheries in the Middle East, and also manufactured carpets and latex products. He later moved on to real estate development and construction. David immigrated to the U.S. in 1970, and initially lived in the San Francisco Bay area. He loved and appreciated his life in the United States and taught his family that America is a blessed land of opportunity. David was the patriarch of his extended family. He deeply cared about the welfare of his loved ones and they frequently sought his wise advice. He believed in giving back to his community and frequently reminded those around him to fully appreciate the freedoms guaranteed to Americans. In 1972 a real estate agent introduced David to a business opportunity located on the southern outskirts of Reno, Nevada. It was a 142-room motor lodge and coffee shop named Golden Door. David purchased it, and it was run initially under his ownership as the Golden Road Motel. Eventually the motel was transferred to the ownership of David's children, and with David's vision and guidance, the property ultimately became today's Atlantis Casino Resort Spa, a premier destination resort. In addition to his interest in business and love for family, David was an active member of Reno's Temple Emanuel and the United Jewish Appeal. In 2009 the David and Parvin Farahi Jewish Day School opened at the Aleph Academy in Reno, named in honor of David and his wife. David passed on peacefully at home in Reno on June 24, 2012, surrounded by his loving family. In accordance with his wishes, David was laid to rest in the Holy City of Jerusalem, Israel, on June 27, in the presence of his family and friends. He is survived by his wife of 64 years, Parvin; son John and wife Catherine; son Bahram ("Bob") and wife Parinaz; son Behrouz ("Ben") and wife Susan (all of Reno); daughter Jila and husband Joseph (of Los Angeles); sister Moluk Saeedi (of Los Angeles); brother Abraham (of Reno); and his twelve adoring grandchildren, all born in Reno.A memorial service will be held on Tuesday July 10th at 5:30 p.m. at Temple Emanuel, located at the corner of Lakeside and Manzanita Ln.



Published in Reno Gazette-Journal on July 8, 2012


